    "body": "@eggplantzzz You are absolutelly right! Thanks for taking the time to answer.\r\nI think it's worth explaining that I was mislead by the VSCode extension that was signaling an error on the import, while `truffle compile` was indeed.\r\n\r\nTo make things work, I had to change a little bit of my VSCode configuration, so it probably matches the Truffle way of invoking the compiler.\r\n\r\nFor those interested, the interesting bits are `solidity.packageDefaultDependenciesDirectory` and `solidity.packageDefaultDependenciesContractsDirectory` VSCode extension settings:\r\nIt occured to me that the first one has a correct default of `node_modules`, but the second one has an incorrect default of `contracts` (So the VSCode extension does a weird string interpolation using both as explained [here](https://github.com/juanfranblanco/vscode-solidity), look for \"Openzeppelin\").\r\n\r\nWith these settings, you would be able to import things from `node_modules` properly during both project dev compilation and as a dependency itself.",
